The error handling strategy here is concerning. We're catching all exceptions and continuing, which could lead to silent failures in production. Consider implementing:

```typescript
class PipelineError extends Error {
  constructor(
    message: string,
    public stage: PipelineStage,
    public retryable: boolean
  ) {
    super(message);
  }
}
```

This would give us better visibility into failures and allow for smart retry logic.

This synchronous loop is blocking the event loop. We should refactor to use async iteration:

```typescript
for await (const batch of dataStream) {
  await processBatch(batch);
}
```

This would allow other operations to proceed while processing.

The transformation logic here is O(n²) complexity. For large datasets this will be prohibitively slow. Consider using a Map for lookups:

```typescript
const lookupMap = new Map(referenceData.map(item => [item.id, item]));
const transformed = data.map(row => ({
  ...row,
  enriched: lookupMap.get(row.refId)
}));
```

This reduces complexity to O(n) and should improve performance by 100x for typical datasets.
